The christening ceremony, held on Saturday in San Diego, was initially set to include Lewis himself, but he passed away from pancreatic cancer before the unveiling. Commemorating the civil rights icon, Woodward spoke about the ways in which Lewis’ legacy lives on. ‘John Lewis lives in all the spaces where people reach out their hands to pull others up to the lives that they deserve,’ she said.

Lewis, who served as the representative for Georgia’s 5th Congressional District for more than three decades, dedicated his life to fighting nonviolently for civil rights, insisting that ‘The vote is the most powerful nonviolent tool we have.’

Lewis fought alongside Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. throughout the Civil Rights movement, leading the 1965 voting rights march on the Edmund Pettus Bridge in Selma, AL, and surviving a brutal police beating that left him hospitalized.

Often seen as the moral conscience of Congress, he urged Americans to ‘get in good trouble, necessary trouble,’ in the fight for civil rights.

The 742-foot-long vessel named for Lewis is designed to refuel Navy carrier strike group ships operating at sea, according to the Navy.

‘Civil Service Mariners will operate this ship with the skill, resolve and courage displayed by John Lewis. With this ship, our naval service is better positioned to meet the challenges that lie ahead,’ said Rear Admiral Michael Wettlaufer, commander of Military Sealift Command.

The naming of the Navy ship is one of several tributes planned in honor of Lewis. The city of Atlanta unveiled a statue of Lewis in June; in Nashville, a stretch of Fifth Avenue was formally renamed after the Congressman; and nationwide, Americans gathered to hold vigils, marches, and celebrations to honor Lewis’ life and legacy.

Vanessa Wyche will head up the Johnson Space Center in Houston, Texas—making her the first Black woman to lead one of NASA's centers.⁠
⁠
The South Carolina native, who has served as Johnson's acting director since May 3, is a 31-year veteran of NASA and has been involved in multiple space shuttle missions as flight manager, in addition to working within the executive office of the NASA administrator.⁠
⁠
'As the home to America’s astronaut corps, International Space Station mission operations, the Orion and Gateway programs, and a host of future space developments, Johnson is a world leader in human space exploration and is playing a key role in the next giant leaps in American excellence in space,' Wyche said in a statement. 'I look forward to working with everyone as we push forward to the Moon and inspire a new generation of explorers to reach for the stars.'⁠
⁠
⁠

node.text:
Research published in The Lancet's EClinical Medicine journal found that a significant number of patients with COVID-19 have experienced prolonged symptoms, known as Long COVID. One estimate using data from Johns Hopkins University posits that 10% of people who survived COVID-19, or 3.3M Americans, are living with persistent, debilitating symptoms that can affect their lives for months or even years after infection.⁠
⁠
According to the World Health Organization, the total number of COVID-19 cases has exceeded 190M globally, with the death toll surpassing 4M. The Lancet research surveyed 4,000 people from 56 countries that reported 203 various symptoms in the 7 months between Dec 2019 and May 2020, ranging from rashes, peeling skin, and digestive issues, to muscle spasms, hearing loss, and tinnitus. For COVID-19 'long haulers,' the most commonly mentioned persisting symptoms were fatigue, brain fog, and post-exertional malaise.⁠
⁠
The study argues that COVID-19 is not just a respiratory illness that doesn't necessarily leave the body, but also that it can lead to severely debilitating symptoms. Almost 45% of the research participants reported needing a reduced work schedule because of their illness, and 22% were unable to work at all.⁠
Experts still need to research Long COVID more but estimated that more than 90% of the cohort studied still experienced symptoms after 6 months.⁠
⁠

A week after catching heat from President Joe Biden for inadequately moderating anti-vaccination misinformation on its platform, Facebook has blocked the hashtag 'Vaccines Kill.' Instagram, which Facebook owns, de-platformed the Vaccines Kill hashtag two years ago.⁠
⁠
'Now, the [Vaccines Kill] hashtag on Facebook violates our policies against misinformation about COVID-19 and vaccines and we've blocked it from search,' a company spokesperson told CNN.⁠

First lady Jill Biden arrived in Tokyo on Thursday as part of a five-day trip to kick off the Summer Olympics. ⁠
⁠
Biden will lead the U.S. delegation in an opening ceremony amid concerns over COVID-19 as cases rise in Japan.⁠

Biden is set to meet virtually with members of Team USA and co-host a watch party with foreign service officers for the U.S. embassy in Tokyo for the U.S. Mexico softball game on Saturday. ⁠
⁠
This visit to Tokyo marks Biden’s first solo trip as first lady.⁠

node.text:
Chicago’s new civilian police oversight committee—dubbed the Community Commission for Public Safety and Accountability—has been decades in the making.⁠
⁠
It’s ‘the most transformative police oversight legislation in the country,’ Desmond Yancy, director of Chicago’s Inner-City Muslim Action Network, told the Washington Post. The city of Chicago’s police department has been plagued for years by allegations of corruption and scandal; the formation of this committee is being heralded as a major advancement in the national push for police reform, a conversation that recently came to a head during the Black Lives Matter protests of summer 2020. And it will give the people of Chicago a more direct say in how the city’s police are run.⁠
⁠
The committee will consist of 7 elected members, each of whom will serve 4-year terms beginning in 2023. Candidates will be nominated by three-person councils from each of Chicago’s 22 police districts. At least two members must be active attorneys, while the others might consist of civil rights activists and those with backgrounds in mental health and social work, per the Washington Post.⁠
⁠
⁠
#chicago #publicsafety #accountability #antiracism

'It never occurred to me after three highly effective vaccines were developed in under a year we'd have difficulty getting Americans to take the shots.'

Senate Minority Leader Mitch McConnell, supported by other GOP lawmakers, urged Americans to get vaccinated 'as rapidly as possible,' in order to avoid an even greater surge in COVID-19 cases similar to what the country saw last fall. However, the GOP figurehead stopped short of criticizing specific conservative voices and members of his own party who've espoused dangerous anti-vaccine rhetoric in the past.

McConnell has another reason he's been particularly vocal about Americans getting inoculated: He's a polio survivor. 'I say this with some authority, as you all know, as a result of being a polio victim myself and being very aware that took seven decades to come up with two effective polio vaccines. This was done in under one year.'
